  },
  "hasValidationResult": [
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/validation/rh-index-comparison-5pt",
      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "Relative Hemolysis Index Comparison — 5-Point Flow-Speed Sweep (Primary Validation)",
      "description": "This validation result captures the outcome of the primary model-experiment comparison for the FDA generic centrifugal blood pump across five flow-speed operating points (2 L/min at 2500 RPM, 3 L/min at 3000 RPM, 4 L/min at 3500 RPM, 5 L/min at 4000 RPM, and 6 L/min at 4500 RPM). The CFD-predicted relative hemolysis index (RHI) was computed using the Giersiepen-Wurzinger power-law damage accumulation model integrated along Lagrangian particle trajectories seeded uniformly at the pump inlet. Experimental hemolysis measurements were obtained from the Morrison et al. (2016) in vitro loop study using bovine blood at 37°C, with normalized index of hemolysis (NIH) converted to RHI via the Heuser-Opitz normalization. Agreement between CFD prediction and experiment was assessed using the V&V 40 output comparison metric: all five operating points yielded RHI_CFD / RHI_exp ratios within the acceptance band of 0.75–1.25, with the worst-case ratio of 1.19 observed at the 2 L/min condition where recirculation zones are most pronounced. The model correctly rank-ordered all five operating points by hemolysis severity, confirming its utility for identifying worst-case conditions. Grid convergence was verified independently (see discretization error factor), and turbulence model sensitivity was bounded by a k-ω SST versus RSM comparison showing less than 8% variation in predicted RHI across all operating points. This result was compiled and reviewed by the computational fluid dynamics team lead and the independent verification engineer during the Q3 2024 credibility review cycle, with supporting data archived in the hemolysis-experimental-measurements dataset. No structured prov:wasGeneratedBy activity reference is recorded in this evidence package because the result was assembled from pre-existing archived simulation runs and experimental logs rather than from a single traceable computational activity; the narrative above is intended to provide equivalent transparency regarding the generation process.",
      "comparedAgainst": "https://uofa.net/morrison/data/hemolysis-experimental-measurements"
    },
